               <p>JAMES SMITH. I am a <rs id="t18280410-115-viclabel629" type="occupation">tobacconist</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280410-115-victim750 t18280410-115-viclabel629"></join>, and live at <placeName id="t18280410-115-crimeloc630">No. 27. Quadrant</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18280410-115-crimeloc630" type="placeName" value="No. 27. Quadrant"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18280410-115-crimeloc630" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280410-115-off627 t18280410-115-crimeloc630"></join>. On the evening of the 28th of March, between nine and ten o'clock, I and my wife were in the parlour; she heard something, and went into the shop; the prisoner was there - he asked for a situation; she said, she knew of none; but on looking round, she saw a gap in the boxes in the window - I went out and seized the prisoner; I asked if he had taken any boxes, he said, No, I said, if he had not, he knew who had; I searched him, but found nothing - I fetched the watchman who found these three boxes in his breeches; I had boxes of this description in my window, and I believe these to be mine - he must have reached out his arm to get them.</p>
